<subSubSection lastPageId="90" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="87.[151,1437,1728,2042]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1728,1754]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[281,402,1729,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Paraclorindaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vesperis">
<emphasis box="[281,402,1729,1754]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">P. vesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[775,948,1728,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Paraclorindaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[775,948,1728,1754]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Paraclorindaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the anterior margin of the head not thin or foliaceous, male pygofer short in lateral view and square shaped and with short posteroventral tooth, subgenital plates meeting medially, and aedeagus symmetrical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[151,1437,1728,2042]" box="[199,635,1836,1863]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,267,1837,1863]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Body.</emphasis>
Male, 
<quantity box="[345,431,1837,1863]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
to forewing apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[151,1437,1728,2042]" box="[199,851,1872,1899]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,272,1872,1898]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Color.</emphasis>
As in genus description. Relatively lightly colored.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[151,1437,1728,2042]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,267,1909,1935]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Male.</emphasis>
Pygofer short, quadrate; with four relatively long thick setae posterodorsally; posteroventral tooth distinct, sharply pointed, not long or claw-like. Subgenital plates triangular; meeting along median margins; laterally with numerous short, thick setae; with two loosely arranged rows of longer setae sublaterally, reaching nearly to middle of plate. Apical flange of aedeagus in caudal view with marginal crenulations.
</paragraph>
